WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
My name is Dewey Dunnington, I'm a software engineer at Evoltron Data, and I'm a developer

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:15.920
on the Apache Arrow project, where I get to work on cool things like geospatial data and

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:20.280
R. One of the things that came out of that is the GRO package, which takes my favorite

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:24.480
things about Arrow, and my favorite things about R, which is rspatial, and puts them

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:25.480
together.

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:30.280
My first favorite thing about the Arrow package are parquet files.

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:35.360
So parquet files are a little bit like CSVs in that you can read and write tables, but

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:39.919
they're binary, so they're smaller, and they're faster to read and write, and they remember

00:00:39.919 --> 00:00:40.919
your data type.

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:43.360
So if you write a date to a parquet file, you get a date back.

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:47.279
If you write a number to a parquet file, you get a number back.

00:00:47.279 --> 00:00:52.000
With GeoArrow, if you write an sf object to a parquet file, you get an sf object back,

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.720
which is really useful, and it turns out that it's also really fast.

00:00:54.959 --> 00:00:58.880
So if you find yourself waiting for your files to load, try parquet.

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:03.360
If you find yourself waiting for your geospatial files to load, try GeoArrow read-view-parquet.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:09.879
My second favorite thing about the Arrow package are datasets.

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:13.440
Datasets let you take a whole lot of files that you create, and you can split them up

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:19.760
however you want, and you can query them like they're a database.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:24.400
In this example, I have a whole bunch of parking interactions from the city of Philadelphia,

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:26.959
and I have them hosted on an S3 bucket.

00:01:26.959 --> 00:01:29.000
They could be on my computer, too.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.720
Here, using the Arrow package, I can open them as a dataset, and I can query them using

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:38.320
DeepLyer, and when I hit collect, Arrow takes care of the details.

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:40.080
And there's a lot of details to take care of.

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:45.120
Arrow pulls the data from a remote data source or from your computer, and Arrow runs your

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:49.879
query in parallel using all the cores on your computer, and it splits up the data into manageable

00:01:49.879 --> 00:01:52.879
chunks just in case the dataset is bigger than your memory.

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:56.959
A lot of geospatial data is really big, and a lot of it is bigger than memory, so this

00:01:56.959 --> 00:02:03.199
lets you use that workflow with geospatial data, and it just works.

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:07.360
The final thing is something that a lot of users don't think about, but it's something

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:13.039
that I'm really passionate about as an rspatial package maintainer, which is simplifying possibly

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:17.080
how to maintain all of the components that make up the rspatial ecosystem and how they

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:18.080
fit together.

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:22.720
There's a lot of components, and they all come together, hopefully silently, to make

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:26.679
your experience as an rspatial user awesome.

00:02:26.679 --> 00:02:30.639
But there's a lot of interactions, and there's a lot of people that spend a lot of time managing

00:02:30.639 --> 00:02:34.520
all of those interactions and maintaining them.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:38.720
GeoArrow uses a data structure that we can pass between all of those, which means that

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:43.600
we can define an interaction for every single component rather than every single pair of

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:48.360
components, which is a lot less maintenance work, and it means that rspatial developers

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:53.880
like me can spend more time adding features, which is fun, and less time fixing bugs, which

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:57.479
is less fun.

00:02:57.479 --> 00:03:01.279
And finally, because that thing that we're passing around is an Arrow array, we get all

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:06.000
of the Arrow ecosystem at our disposal, which includes the Arrow package, Parquet files

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.360
and datasets, but also the wider Arrow ecosystem, which includes bindings for Python and Rust

00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:15.000
and Julia and a lot of other languages and a lot of other frameworks that have adopted

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Arrow.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:22.360
The GeoArrow package is still under development, as well as the Apache Arrow integration that

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:26.960
enables this, but if you want to follow along, you can follow me on Twitter or follow me

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:30.880
on GitHub, or visit my website where I blog about all sorts of incredibly nerdy things

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:33.240
involving geospatial, R, and Arrow.

